Preparing the environment

Installing R and RStudio

For this training, we will use:

  1. R ‚Äì a free software environment for statistical computing and graphics (download and install from https://cloud.r-project.org/)
  2. RStudio ‚Äì an integrated development environment for R (download and install from https://rstudio.com/products/rstudio/download/)
  3. Packages ‚Äì extend the capabilities of R. To install a package, open RStudio then
    • Packages ‚Äì> Install ‚Äì> type the package name in Packages ‚Äì> Install or
    • Type install.packages("package_name") then hit Enter key
      • e.g.: install.packages(“plotly”)

Preparing the data

Example study

Suppose we have three datasets from a study:

  • recruitment.xlsx ‚Äì data collected during the participant recruitment
  • clinic_visit1.xlsx ‚Äì data from the first clinic visit
  • clinic_visit2.xlsx ‚Äì data from the second clinic visit, has the same variables as clinic_visit1.xlsx

Preparing the data

Creating new variables

  • Create age at recruitment in days (age_d) and in years (age_y) variables in the recdata frame

  • Check the tidyverse‚Äôs lubridate package for more advanced date/time manipulation

Preparing the data

Joining data frames vertically (appending)

  • cv1 and cv2 have the same variables (columns), let‚Äôs combine them vertically

Preparing the data

Reshaping data

  • The cvs data frame has data from different visits of the same study participant in different rows ‚Äì this is called long format

  • We would like to have the data from all visits of the same participant in the same row ‚Äì this is called wide format

  • Use pivot_longer() to reshape from wide to long format

Preparing the data

Joining data frames horizontally (merging)

  • Now that we have all visits‚Äô data in one row per participant, we would like to joint them with the corresponding participant data from the recruitment (rec)

Preparing the data

Recode categorical variables

  • The variable sex is stored as numeric (1 and 2), where 1=Female and 2=Male
  • marital_status is stored as sing (Single), marr (Married), divo (Divorced) and wido (Widowed)

Preparing the data

Subsetting data ‚Äì rows (observations)

  • dataframe_name[row_selection,]
  • row_selection can be a
    • vector of row numbers
      • rcv[2,] returns the 2nd row
      • rcv[c(1,3,7),] returns 1st, 3rd and 7th rows
    • logical vector (TRUE/FALSE) whose length is equal to the total number of rows of the data frame
      • returns rows in positions where the vector has the value TRUE
      • it is often given as a logical condition involving the operators < (less than), <= (less than or equal to), >, >=, == (equal to), != (not equal), ! (not), | (or), & (and), is.na() (returns true for missing values, NA)

Preparing the data

Subsetting data ‚Äì rows

Examples:

Preparing the data

Subsetting data ‚Äì columns (variables)

  • dataframe_name[,column_selection]
  • colu_selection can be a
    • vector of column numbers to keep or drop
      • rcv[,c(1,3,5)] keeps the 1st, 3rd and 5th columns
      • rcv[,-c(1,3,5)] drops the 1st, 3rd and 5th columns
    • vector of column names to keep
      • `rcv[,c(“subjectid”, “sex”, “marital_status”)]

Preparing the data

Subsetting data ‚Äì notes

  • You can combine row and column subsetting in one step

  • Any operation with a missing value (NA) results in a missing value, so to check if a variable x is NA use is.na(x) instead of x==NA

  • Check the tidyverse‚Äôs dbplyr package for more advanced data manipulation

Preparing the data

Saving data frame to a file

  • You can easily save your R data frames in different file formats using the rio package
